Date: Tue 16 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC News, Tue 16 Nov 2004 [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/kent/4016867.stm>

England: emergency vaccinations for mumps offered in Kent
---------------------------------------------------------
Dr Mathi Chandrakumar, director of the Kent Health Protection Unit,
announced a mumps vaccination program, after cases rose from 39 last year
[2003] to 113 so far in 2004. Dr Chandrakumar said the rise was not an
epidemic, but protection was needed. Health officials are targeting up to
30 000 at-risk teenagers at 8 tertiary education sites.
Dr Chandrakumar told BBC South East Today: "We don't need to be worried as
long as this campaign is successful, and we can prevent large numbers of
cases. We know it works, because, when we had an outbreak in the University
of Kent, we carried out a campaign, and we stopped it in its tracks; we did
not have any further cases." The mumps immunization centers include the
following: Canterbury College (Canterbury); Christchurch University College
(Canterbury and Thanet); South Kent College (Ashford); West Kent College
(Tonbridge); Oakwood Park Centre (Maidstone); and Mid Kent College (City
Way site).
Dr Chandrakumar said outbreaks were occurring in people too old to have
been offered measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) jabs routinely as children.
The MMR program only started in 1988. Dr Chandrakumar said the vaccination
was "perfectly safe" and did not have any serious side effects.
Kent University completed a round of immunizations for new students at the
start of term in late October 2004. Other UK universities are also
launching mass MMR vaccinations to stem the mumps threat.
Mumps is a viral infection that is transmitted through airborne droplets
from the coughs and sneezes of infected people. It takes about 16 to 21
days between coming into contact with an infected person and the appearance
of symptoms, such as painful swelling of saliva-making glands found on
either side of the face. The vast majority of people make an easy recovery
from mumps infection. However, it can rarely cause unpleasant and painful
complications and can be particularly dangerous in young men who may
develop swelling of the testis that can cause infertility.
