Source: Cambridge News, Tue 16 Nov 2004 [edited]
<http://w3.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/story.asp?StoryID=64957>

England: meningitis warning for Cambridge students
--------------------------------------------------
Students in Cambridge could be at risk from a new outbreak of the
potentially deadly illness meningitis. This is the warning issued by the
medical charity the Meningitis Trust. They say the recent outbreak of mumps
among university students could lead to an increase in cases of particular
strains of viral meningitis, because the viruses that cause both illnesses
are closely linked. Although the strains of meningitis concerned are very
rarely lethal, they can lead to severe side effects and after effects such
as headaches, fever, joint pain and stiffness in the neck, diarrhea,
vomiting, and aversion to light.
In total, 38 students have been struck down with mumps so far this term,
compared with a recent average of only one or 2 per academic year.
University authorities are urging students under 24 years of age to take
the triple MMR vaccine, which prevents mumps, measles, and rubella.
Bridie Taylor, community services manager with the Meningitis Trust, said
that most of the current generation of students at Cambridge had not
received the triple vaccine, because it was not introduced until the late
1980s, after their infancy. But some symptoms of mumps are similar to those
of meningitis, and Miss Taylor said: "the incubation period for mumps is
anything up to 3 weeks."
"We do not want GPs to be inundated. But, it is an especially nasty kind of
illness, and we want people to be aware of the risks. If any of these
symptoms persist for more than 3 weeks, people should seek medical help."
