Date: Tue 16 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The National Student, November 2004 [edited]
<http://www.national-student.co.uk/2004_11/national_news_mumps.htm>

UK: students are being warned of an imminent mumps epidemic
-----------------------------------------------------------
Universities and colleges from the Scottish Highlands to Cornwall are
reporting massive increases in mumps cases this year [2004]. The problem is
being taken seriously in all areas. The Edinburgh Evening News reports that
"thousands of students are being offered a vaccine against mumps, after
cases in the Lothians soared 5-fold in a year." The number of suspected
cases in Grampian region alone has risen to 10 times what it was last year
[2003]. There had been 37 confirmed cases in Grampian region, 53 in Tayside
and 18 across the Highlands and Islands. In the same period, suspected
cases in Grampian have risen to 88, compared to just 8 for the whole of
2003. Almost all of the cases involve adolescents aged 13 to 25, with the
majority falling into the 17 to 20 age group.
Dr Arun Mukarjee, an expert in communicable diseases at NHS Grampian, said
that the age group accounted for about 50 per cent of the number of
reported cases this year [2004], and the high incidence of mumps could be
explained by the introduction of the MMR vaccine when they were children.
"The MMR vaccine was introduced in 1988," he said. "Initially, we started
with one dose, and the uptake was very good. As a result, mumps and measles
were almost eradicated in this country. We soon realized that not one but 2
doses of MMR were needed to give over 99 per cent protection from mumps,
so, in 1996, we gave a 2nd dose, but those born between 1984 and 1987
missed out."
Dr Mukarjee said youngsters born between those dates would have received a
2nd measles and rubella vaccine, introduced in 1996 [this was actually a
one-off campaign late in 1994. See
<http://www.hpa.org.uk/cdr/CDRreview/1994/cdrr1294.pdf> - Mod.SH], but the
jab would not protect them against mumps. "No one knows why cases are on
the increase for this age group this year [2004], as opposed to last year
or next year," he added. "What we do know is that the disease spreads like
wildfire in areas like universities." Health authorities have written to GP
practices around the north and north-east [of Scotland] asking them to
conduct selective immunization for young people aged 17 to 20.
In England, there is a similar picture. The Bath Chronicle reports that
"thousands of adults are to be offered vaccinations to prevent a mumps
epidemic in Bath. A program of inoculations is being devised to target 16
to 25 year olds, after a massive increase in cases of the infection over
the past year." The Express reported that "an outbreak of mumps has struck
85 1st year students at one university. Mass vaccination schemes are being
set up over fears of an epidemic sweeping the country." Colleagues of
students at Exeter University have been offered vaccinations, and 1000 1st
year students have so far been given the MMR jab. Stuart Franklin, a
spokesman for the university, said that "it is too early to say we are on
top of the situation, but in the last few days the number of cases has
dropped off." Oxford, Manchester, Leeds, Kent, Nottingham, and Birmingham
universities have all recently reported outbreaks of mumps. Official
figures show a dramatic rise in cases from 180 in 1996 to 3756 so far this
year. The number of cases of mumps reported at Lancaster University has
risen to 30, as health bosses warn of a national outbreak among students,
reports the Lancaster Guardian. In Plymouth, extra immunization clinics are
being added at the Bailrigg campus, as the capacity to administer MMR jabs
has been totally outstripped by demand, says the Western Morning News. Lynn
Jones, practice director at the Bailrigg Health Centre, said "we had 500
immunization packs ready for students on Tuesday [16 Nov 2004], so we were
completely unprepared when nearly 1000 turned up, and we had to turn the
rest away." In recent weeks, Exeter University has had 76 confirmed cases
of mumps in 3 of its halls of residence on campus, and 300 of its students
have already received the MMR vaccine.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Remarkably, the mumps epidemic in young people in the 17 20 year age range
is now affecting those attending universities and tertiary education
institutions throughout the UK and Ireland. It is believed that the high
susceptibility of this age group relates to the fact that these young
people have received only a single mumps vaccination, which appears not to
be sufficient to confer complete protection. However, it is not clear why
the incidence of mumps is higher in 2004 than in immediately preceding
years. A warning of increased risk of viral meningitis, as a consequence of
the mumps epidemic, has been issued by the Meningitis Trust, although the
extent of the risk, and the viral pathogen(s) involved, have not been
specified. Central Nervous System (CNS) involvement during acute mumps
virus infection occurs at such high frequency that it has been considered
to be a primary manifestation of mumps, rather than a complication. The
consequences of CNS infection caused by mumps virus infection extend from
aseptic meningitis (common and mild) to fulminant encephalitis (rare but
life threatening). The term mumps meningoencephalitis has been coined to
cover the range of intermediate manifestations of mumps virus infection of
the CNS. - Mod.CP]
